<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1341,1835]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">
<typeStatus box="[151,207,1341,1367]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">Type</typeStatus>
data: This species was described based on an undetermined number of females collected in 
<collectingCountry box="[1237,1309,1341,1367]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Lepeletier, A. L. M." box="[180,376,1377,1403]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27" refId="ref10183" refString="Lepeletier, A. L. M. (1841) Histoire Naturelle des Insectes. Hymenopteres. Vol. 2. Roret, Paris, 680 pp." type="book" year="1841">Lepeletier (1841)</bibRefCitation>
the exemplars he used were housed at 
<collectionCode box="[816,898,1377,1403]" country="USA" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/3kvn-7rck" name="Princeton University" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">MNHP</collectionCode>
. Unfortunately, there were not found specimens under this name in that collection or in 
<collectionCode box="[618,727,1413,1439]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">OUMNH</collectionCode>
. Apparently, these specimens have been lost for a long time, because 
<bibRefCitation author="Moure, J. S." box="[251,411,1449,1476]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27" pagination="114 - 123" refId="ref10442" refString="Moure, J. S. (1969) Notas sobre algumas especies de Centris da Guiana (Hym., Apoidea). Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ciencias, 41, 114 - 123." type="journal article" year="1969">Moure (1969)</bibRefCitation>
also failed in finding it some decades ago. According to this author (
<bibRefCitation author="Moure, J. S." box="[1232,1383,1449,1476]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27" pagination="114 - 123" refId="ref10442" refString="Moure, J. S. (1969) Notas sobre algumas especies de Centris da Guiana (Hym., Apoidea). Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ciencias, 41, 114 - 123." type="journal article" year="1969">Moure, 1969</bibRefCitation>
) the 
<typeStatus box="[151,199,1485,1511]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">type</typeStatus>
specimens were obtained from Auguste François César Prouvençal de Saint-Hilaire (
<date box="[1179,1310,1484,1511]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27" value="1779" valueMax="1853">1779–1853</date>
), a famous French entomologist and botanist who lived in 
<collectingCountry box="[683,751,1521,1547]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="27">Brazil</collectingCountry>
between 
<date box="[860,1031,1521,1547]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27" value="1816" valueMax="1822">1816 and 1822</date>
. When he returned to Paris in 1822, he brought approximately 16,000 insects (
<bibRefCitation author="Shampo, M. A. &amp; Kyle, R. A." box="[634,897,1557,1583]" pageId="4" pageNumber="27" pagination="836" refId="ref11179" refString="Shampo, M. A. &amp; Kyle, R. A. (1988) Augusto de Saint-Hilaire: French entomologist and botanist. Mayo Clinic Proceedings, 63, 836. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0025 - 6196 (12) 62368 - 4" type="journal article" year="1988">Shampo &amp; Kyle, 1988</bibRefCitation>
), probably including some of which Lepeletier studied and described later.
</paragraph>
